## The most important module in this course

That is not an exaggeration. `useEffect` bugs are the single most common category of React bugs, the most common mistakes AI makes when generating React code, and the concept that causes the most confusion. If you leave this course understanding one thing deeply, make it useEffect.

The good news: for reading code, you only need to understand three patterns.

## What useEffect does

A React component is a function that returns JSX -- it describes what the user sees. But sometimes a component needs to **do** something beyond rendering: fetch data from a server, set up a timer, update the document title, listen for window resizing.

These are called **side effects** -- things that happen beyond just showing markup on the screen.

`useEffect` is React's way of saying: "After you render, also do this other thing."

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  // This code runs AFTER the component renders
  document.title = `You have ${count} messages`;
}, [count]);
```

### The anatomy of useEffect

Every useEffect has two parts:

1. **The effect function** -- the code to run (first argument)
2. **The dependency array** -- when to run it (second argument)

```jsx
useEffect(
  () => { /* what to do */ },   // Part 1: the effect
  [dependency1, dependency2]      // Part 2: when to do it
);
```

The dependency array is the key to reading useEffect. It tells you **when** the effect runs.

## The three patterns

### Pattern 1: Run once on mount -- `[]`

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  fetchUserProfile();
}, []);
```

An empty dependency array `[]` means: "Run this effect once, when the component first appears on screen." In React terminology, this is called **mounting**.

This is the most common pattern. You will see it used for:
- Fetching initial data from an API
- Setting up event listeners
- Initializing third-party libraries
- Logging that a page was viewed

When you see `useEffect(() => {...}, [])`, read it as: **"When this component first appears, do this."**

### Pattern 2: Run when something changes -- `[dep]`

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  fetchUser(userId);
}, [userId]);
```

A dependency array with values means: "Run this effect when the component first appears AND whenever any of these values change."

In this example, the effect runs:
1. When the component first mounts
2. Every time `userId` changes to a different value

Common uses:
- Re-fetching data when a filter changes
- Updating the page title when a value changes
- Syncing state with local storage

When you see `useEffect(() => {...}, [userId])`, read it as: **"Whenever userId changes, do this."**

You can have multiple dependencies:

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  searchProducts(query, category);
}, [query, category]);
```

This runs whenever `query` OR `category` changes.

### Pattern 3: Run after every render -- no array

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  console.log('Component rendered');
});
```

No dependency array at all means: "Run this effect after every single render." This is almost always a mistake. If the effect does something that causes a state change (which triggers a re-render, which runs the effect again, which triggers another state change...), you get an **infinite loop**.

**When you see a useEffect with no dependency array, treat it as a red flag.** It is occasionally intentional, but more often it is a bug -- especially in AI-generated code.

### The cheat sheet

| Dependency array | When the effect runs | Common use |
| :-- | :-- | :-- |
| `[]` | Once, when the component first appears | Initial data fetch, setup |
| `[value]` | On mount + whenever `value` changes | Re-fetch when filter/id changes |
| `[a, b]` | On mount + whenever `a` or `b` changes | Re-fetch when any dependency changes |
| *(missing)* | After every single render | Usually a bug |

## The infinite loop -- React's most common bug

This is so important it gets its own section. Here is the classic infinite loop:

```jsx
function UserProfile({ userId }) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);

  // BUG: infinite loop!
  useEffect(() => {
    fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`)
      .then(res => res.json())
      .then(data => setUser(data));
  }); // <-- Missing dependency array!

  return <div>{user ? user.name : 'Loading...'}</div>;
}
```

What happens:
1. Component renders. Effect runs (no dependency array = runs every render).
2. Effect fetches data. When the data arrives, it calls `setUser(data)`.
3. `setUser` triggers a re-render.
4. Component re-renders. Effect runs again (still no dependency array).
5. Effect fetches data again. Calls `setUser` again.
6. Another re-render. Another fetch. Forever.

The fix is adding a dependency array:

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`)
    .then(res => res.json())
    .then(data => setUser(data));
}, [userId]); // <-- Now it only runs when userId changes
```

This is the number one bug you will encounter when reviewing AI-generated React code. The AI forgets the dependency array, or puts the wrong things in it. When someone reports "the page keeps loading forever" or "the browser tab freezes," check the useEffect dependency arrays first.

## Cleanup functions

Sometimes an effect sets something up that needs to be torn down. A timer that should stop. An event listener that should be removed. A WebSocket connection that should close.

The effect function can **return** a cleanup function:

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  const timer = setInterval(() => {
    setSeconds(prev => prev + 1);
  }, 1000);

  return () => {
    clearInterval(timer);  // This runs when the component is removed
  };
}, []);
```

The cleanup function runs:
- When the component is **removed** from the screen (unmounting)
- **Before** the effect re-runs (if dependencies changed)

When you see `return () => {...}` inside a useEffect, read it as: **"When this component leaves or before this effect re-runs, do this cleanup."**

Common cleanup patterns:

```jsx
// Clearing a timer
return () => clearInterval(timer);

// Removing an event listener
return () => window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);

// Closing a connection
return () => websocket.close();

// Cancelling a subscription
return () => subscription.unsubscribe();
```

Missing cleanup functions are another common source of bugs. If you see a useEffect that sets up a timer or event listener but has no return statement, that is a potential memory leak.

## A real-world example

Here is a realistic component that uses useEffect to fetch user data:

```jsx
function UserProfile({ userId }) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
  const [error, setError] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    setLoading(true);
    setError(null);

    fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`)
      .then(res => {
        if (!res.ok) throw new Error('Failed to fetch');
        return res.json();
      })
      .then(data => {
        setUser(data);
        setLoading(false);
      })
      .catch(err => {
        setError(err.message);
        setLoading(false);
      });
  }, [userId]);

  if (loading) return <Spinner />;
  if (error) return <ErrorMessage message={error} />;
  return <ProfileCard user={user} />;
}
```

Reading this component:
1. **State**: Three pieces -- `user` (null until fetched), `loading` (true to start), `error` (null unless something goes wrong).
2. **Effect**: Runs when `userId` changes. Sets loading to true, clears any previous error, then fetches data.
3. **Rendering**: Shows a spinner while loading, an error message if something went wrong, or the profile card with the data.

This loading/error/success pattern is so common in React that you will see it in almost every component that fetches data. We will explore it in depth in Level 4.

## Your reading strategy for useEffect

1. **Find the dependency array** -- this tells you when the effect runs
2. **Read the effect body** -- this tells you what it does
3. **Check for a cleanup function** -- `return () => {...}` at the end
4. **Ask: could this cause an infinite loop?** -- Does the effect update state that is not in the dependency array, or is the dependency array missing entirely?

